defaultKeith Richter, speaking 
defaultfor Friends of the Earth said, "It is incomprehensible 
defaultthat under the new rules the burning of trees in power stations will be counted as "carbon neutral" despite the preliminary results of DECC's own research showing that it can be worse for the climate t
defaulthan burning coal
default”
default5
default. Other critics pointed out that emissions from indirect land use change and carbon debt received no consideration in the new standards. We conclude that in answer to the Committee’s question of whether the biomass sustainability criteria
default go far enough is a resounding, “NO”.
default&#xa0;defaultWhy does the RHI not seem to promote heat pumps successfully?default&#xa0;
default4
default.1. 
defaultIt’s not the fault of the RHI, but the fault of the pumps as installed. Leaving aside questions of their e
defaultxpense to install
default, 
defaultand 
defaultthe
default disruptiveness of their installation, all too often they do not work properly. 
defaultA study of installed heat pump performance published by the Energy Saving Trust on the 8
defaultth
default September 2010 – “
defaultGetting Warmer: a field trial of heat pumps”
default revealed that the actu
defaultal performance of heat pumps installed in the UK was surprisingly poor. The study was financed by the heat pump industry and based on a sample of sites where pumps had been installed pre-selected by the industry. The study showed that only 1 of the 22 prop
defaulterties with Ground Source Heat Pumps (GSHPs) achieved the implicit minimum EU Directive 
defaultCoP
default of 3
default, and only 9 of the 47 sites with ASHPs achieved the standard. Similar results prevailed in the 
defaultRowntree
default Foundation study in 
defaultYork
default. The Association for the Conse
defaultrvation of Energy calculates C
defaulto
defaultefficients of Performance for Air Source Heat Pumps from international data of between 2.15 and 2.7. On that basis, they all fail the renewable test.
default4
default.2. 
defaultDECC is well aware of the problem: “We are aware that systems 
defaultinstalled in the past have not always worked as well as they should” (Para. 199, DECC Consultation on the RHI, 20
defaultth
default September 2012) and again: “It is a common 
defaultfeature in field trials and assessments that there is a significant gap between expected and actu
defaultal performance” (
defaultpara
default. 1.23, 
defaultMicrogeneration
default Strategy Consultation, DECC, 22
defaultnd
default Dec, 2010). DECC is currently monitoring 150 heat pumps and preliminary results show that most heat pumps operating on a 
defaultmild
default Spring day were achieving below the required perfor
defaultmance levels - some significantly below. Far from backing a winning horse, DECC is backing a flop but it has been coy in admitting it, confining itself so far to admit: “We think it is likely that on average the results will still be a long way off the hig
defaulth-performing systems that are consistently being measured in Germany”. 
default&#xa0;
default4.3. 
defaultThe Energy Savings Trust has now published Phase 2 of its testing on pumps (“The Heat is On”, May 2013). The bulk of this work involved a series of interventions on 32 of the fai
defaultling Phase 1 sites over a three year period. In 12 cases the “interventions were “major”. In 10 cases, the interventions involved the complete replacement of the pump systems. Even with all this no doubt expensive intervention: “Some sites did not improve,
default even with major and medium interventions”. The deficiency in performance was especially marked for ASHPs with 
default6
default out of 15 
defaultstill 
defaultfailing to make the 
defaultrenewable 
defaultgrade. From this we deduce that there is no case for continued taxpayer subsidy to ASHPs since ev
defaulten after extensive and costly intervention by experts 
defaultan unacceptable proportion
default could not be made to work properly. They would be ruled out as renewable by the EU and energy they generate would not count towards the 
defaultUK
default’s renewable targets. The average per
defaultformance of ASHPs was under the bar of being counted as renewable.
default4.4. 
defaultTo be fair, after all this desperate effort over three years, most GSHPs did work properly. How much all this extensive and expensive remediation would cost, and who would bear that co
defaultst – the installer or the householder – is a question for bitter experience in the market, but we draw a strong 
defaultconclusion from this that type-rating technology to a standard is a long way from actual installed performance. Let the buyer beware – and let t
defaulthe taxpayer beware of pouring subsidy into a technology that does not make the grade. Government should pay out subsidy only on those pumps tested as having delivered
default to minimum performance standards
default after installation.
default4.5. 
defaultThese conclusions echo other studies. Johnson, for instance,  in 
defaultEnergy Policy
default, 2011, vol. 39, issue 3, pages 1369-1381 finds that at UK efficiencies heat-pump footprints (in kg CO2e emitted pe
defaultr kWh delivered) are comparable or higher than footprints of gaseous fuels used in heating. Compared with fossil fuel gas they don’t save carbon.
